<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 7:12<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I2774a4c0630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>7.</label.designator><headtext>Lay and Expert Opinion Testimony</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71fa1f9682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>7:12.</label.designator><headtext>Subjects of expert testimony—Physical condition</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Opinion testimony is admissible to show physical condition. <eos/><bos/>A lay witness may state an opinion about physical condition, such as that a person appeared to be very sick,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic3dab4807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">1</footnote.reference>] if he includes the facts on which his opinion is based.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3dab4817fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">2</footnote.reference>] Only experts may offer opinions concerning diagnosis, treatment, effect, and continuance of a person&apos;s physical condition.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3dab4827fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1997050769" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a518c27fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Hutcheson v. Daniels</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic3dadb907fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">4</footnote.reference>] the plaintiff noticed problems with his left wrist a few days after a collision with defendant and sought medical treatment within four months of the onset of <page no="198"/>these symptoms. <eos/><bos/>The Georgia Court of Appeals held that a jury could conclude from common knowledge that a causal connection existed between the plaintiff&apos;s injury and the accident in light of the short lapse of time between the collision, the onset of symptoms, and receipt of medical treatment. <eos/><bos/>The Court cited <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1990142446" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a603227fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Madden v. Solomon</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic3dadb917fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">5</footnote.reference>] where it also held that a jury could determine, without expert testimony, that medical expenses after an automobile collision were related to injuries sustained in the collision.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>However, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1987022299" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000960" ID="I19a6c6737fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Eberhart v. Morris Brown College</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic3dadb927fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">6</footnote.reference>] the court held that a medical expert was necessary to establish a causal connection between the plaintiff&apos;s injury and his football career due to a gap of several years.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Since a witness can testify about the extent of another person&apos;s intoxication based on his observation,[<footnote.reference refid="Ic3dadb937fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">7</footnote.reference>] the court held in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1990026111" w-seq-number="00021" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a826027fc011ea988285db8533e975"><ital>Chance v. State</ital></cite.query>[<footnote.reference refid="Ic3dadb947fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">8</footnote.reference>] that law enforcement officers could testify that the defendant in a driving-under-the-influence (DUI) case was both under the influence of alcohol and that the extent of the defendant&apos;s drunkenness rendered him “a less safe driver.”<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The trial court cannot discount expert testimony providing evidence of specific causation where a plaintiff is overexposed to a dangerous chemical without conducting the requisite <ital>Daubert</ital> analysis. <eos/><bos/>Further, such proof that exposure to a toxic chemical is dangerous renders moot the question of how many doses it takes to cause the disease, since the only cause of the disease is exposure to the chemical.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3db02a07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">9</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Court of Appeals has rejected expert testimony regarding a defendant&apos;s post-traumatic stress disorder as irrelevant to the issue of criminal intent.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3db02a17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">10</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Court has held that expert testimony is necessary to support a defendant&apos;s claim of justification where they are claiming battered person syndrome.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="Ic3db02a27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132">11</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="Ic3dab4807fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1955105467" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a344027fc011ea988285db8533e975">Northwestern University v. Crisp, 211 Ga. 636, 88 S.E.2d 26 (1955)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1969134038" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a344057fc011ea988285db8533e975">Ashley v. Standard Oil Co., 119 Ga. App. 786, 168 S.E.2d 656 (1969)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3dab4817fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1938106636" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I19a3b9327fc011ea988285db8533e975">Elliott v. Georgia Power Co., 58 Ga. App. 151, 197 S.E. 914 (1938)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3dab4827fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1939106657" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a42e627fc011ea988285db8533e975">Metropolitan Life Ins. Co. v. Saul, 189 Ga. 1, 5 S.E.2d 214 (1939)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1958122427" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a42e657fc011ea988285db8533e975">Gregory v. Ross, 214 Ga. 306, 104 S.E.2d 452 (1958)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1938106446" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="I19a42e687fc011ea988285db8533e975">New York Life Ins. Co. v. Bradford, 57 Ga. App. 657, 196 S.E. 92 (1938)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1951104638" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a42e6b7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Mayo v. McClung, 83 Ga. App. 548, 64 S.E.2d 330 (1951)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1956125614" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a42e6e7fc011ea988285db8533e975">Atlantic Coast Line R. Co. v. Godard, 93 Ga. App. 671, 92 S.E.2d 626 (1956)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1958122382" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a42e717fc011ea988285db8533e975">Emory University v. Lee, 97 Ga. App. 680, 104 S.E.2d 234 (1958)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1968133163" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a42e747fc011ea988285db8533e975">Thomason v. Willingham, 118 Ga. App. 821, 165 S.E.2d 865 (1968)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1972128596" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a42e777fc011ea988285db8533e975">Everett v. Holmes, 126 Ga. App. 208, 190 S.E.2d 568 (1972)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3dadb907fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1997050769" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a566e27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Hutcheson v. Daniels, 224 Ga. App. 560, 481 S.E.2d 567 (1997)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="198"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3dadb917fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1990142446" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a62a327fc011ea988285db8533e975">Madden v. Solomon, 196 Ga. App. 512, 513, 396 S.E.2d 245 (1990)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3dadb927fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1987022299" w-seq-number="00017" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000960" ID="I19a714937fc011ea988285db8533e975">Eberhart v. Morris Brown College, 181 Ga. App. 516, 517, 352 S.E.2d 832, 37 Ed. Law Rep. 720 (1987)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3dadb937fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1981113387" w-seq-number="00018" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a7b0d27fc011ea988285db8533e975">Lawrence v. State, 157 Ga. App. 264, 277 S.E.2d 60 (1981)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1986110981" w-seq-number="00019" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a7b0d57fc011ea988285db8533e975">Luke v. State, 177 Ga. App. 518, 340 S.E.2d 30 (1986)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1986113439" w-seq-number="00020" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a7b0d87fc011ea988285db8533e975">Howard v. State, 177 Ga. App. 589, 340 S.E.2d 212 (1986)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3dadb947fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>8</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="1990026111" w-seq-number="00022" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" w-pinpoint-page="438" ID="I19a874227fc011ea988285db8533e975">Chance v. State, 193 Ga. App. 242, 387 S.E.2d 437, 438 (1989)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3db02a07fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>9</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="2032934934" w-seq-number="00023" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a910627fc011ea988285db8533e975">Fouch v. Bicknell Supply Co., 326 Ga. App. 863, 756 S.E.2d 682 (2014)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3db02a17fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>10</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="2037460840" w-seq-number="00024" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a985927fc011ea988285db8533e975">Brower v. State, 334 Ga. App. 262, 779 S.E.2d 32 (2015)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="Ic3db02a27fc011eab41db41ad1c68132"><label.designator>11</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017119" w-serial-number="2039356355" w-seq-number="00025" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I19a9fac27fc011ea988285db8533e975">McLaughlin v. State, 338 Ga. App. 1, 789 S.E.2d 247 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/><page no="199"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 7:12<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
